hands_on_practices.solution:
Let $M \in \mathbb{C}^{2 \times 2}$ be upper-triangular with entries
$$
M=\begin{pmatrix}
z_{1} & z_{2} \\
0 & z_{3}
\end{pmatrix}.
$$
The matrix $M$ is unitary if and only if $M^{\dagger}M=I$, where $M^{\dagger}$ is the conjugate transpose. We compute
$$
M^{\dagger}=\begin{pmatrix}
\overline{z_{1}} & 0 \\
\overline{z_{2}} & \overline{z_{3}}
\end{pmatrix},
\quad
M^{\dagger}M=\begin{pmatrix}
\overline{z_{1}} & 0 \\
\overline{z_{2}} & \overline{z_{3}}
\end{pmatrix}
\begin{pmatrix}
z_{1} & z_{2} \\
0 & z_{3}
\end{pmatrix}
=
\begin{pmatrix}
|z_{1}|^{2} & \overline{z_{1}}z_{2} \\
\overline{z_{2}}z_{1} & |z_{2}|^{2}+|z_{3}|^{2}
\end{pmatrix}.
$$
Setting $M^{\dagger}M=I$ yields the system
$$
|z_{1}|^{2}=1, \quad \overline{z_{1}}z_{2}=0, \quad |z_{2}|^{2}+|z_{3}|^{2}=1.
$$
From $|z_{1}|^{2}=1$ we have $|z_{1}|=1$ and thus $z_{1}\neq 0$. Therefore $\overline{z_{1}}z_{2}=0$ implies $z_{2}=0$. Substituting $z_{2}=0$ into $|z_{2}|^{2}+|z_{3}|^{2}=1$ gives $|z_{3}|^{2}=1$, hence $|z_{3}|=1$.

These are necessary conditions. They are also sufficient, because if $z_{2}=0$ and $|z_{1}|=|z_{3}|=1$, then
$$
M=\begin{pmatrix}
z_{1} & 0 \\
0 & z_{3}
\end{pmatrix},
\quad
M^{\dagger}=\begin{pmatrix}
\overline{z_{1}} & 0 \\
0 & \overline{z_{3}}
\end{pmatrix},
\quad
M^{\dagger}M=\begin{pmatrix}
|z_{1}|^{2} & 0 \\
0 & |z_{3}|^{2}
\end{pmatrix}
=
I.
$$
Therefore $M \in U(2)$ if and only if $z_{2}=0$ and $|z_{1}|=|z_{3}|=1$, which is exactly the statement in option C.
